  <td style="line-height: 1.5">Sidereal fire (planets)</td>
  <td style="line-height: 1.5">Heaven of the fixed stars</td>
  <td style="line-height: 1.5">Ether (interplanetary medium)</td>
</tr> </tbody>
</table>

<p>
To understand Bacon&rsquo;s theory of matter in the terrestrial
context, we need to pay attention to what have been called
&ldquo;intermediates&rdquo;. These intermediates were combinations of
members from both the Sulphur and Mercury quaternions. In so far as
the heaven of the fixed stars was concerned, the intermediate was a
combination of sidereal fire and ether, where the former was dominant.
On the lowest, subterranean level, the intermediate were salt(s),
subterranean, organic beings, combining Sulphur and Mercury.</p>

<p>
The terrestrial phenomena of minerals, plants and animals were
composed of tangible and pneumatic matter, both of which were a
mixture of the sulphureous and mercurial quaternions. The tangible
salts and juices of plants and animals were watery and oily, and they
had pneumatic matter (spirits) attached that was airy and fiery. Both
spirits and tangibles were material. There was a hierarchy amongst the
terrestrial bodies, which became more complex the higher you moved on
this scale; the lowest bodies were inanimate (metals and stones), the
non-living plants were in the middle and the living animals (including
humans) were on the top. The hierarchy was based on the organization
of spirits (pneumatic matter) inside the bodies. On the lowest level,
in inanimate bodies, spirits were cut off and not inflamed and
kindled. In animate bodies (both plants and animals), spirits were
branched into veins and were kindled and inflamed (Rusu 2018: 452).
Tangible matter was responsible for the species of a body, and its
function was to keep the spirit in the body. Pneumatic matter was the
major source of action in nature whose motion created new individuals
(Rusu 2018: 455; Jalobeanu 2018a: 469&ndash;75).</p>

<p>
Against the fundamental Aristotelian distinction between the sub- and
superlunary regions, Bacon argued that the diurnal motion was not
confined to the heavens. Although the speed of this motion decreased
the closer to the Earth it reached, it accounted for certain
terrestrial phenomena. There was a general westward motion of the air
because air, just like celestial ether, belonged to the Mercury
quaternion. But Bacon also explained the cycle of the tides by the
diurnal motion, which carried the seas westward, only to thrown back
by the corresponding land mass.</p>

<h2 id="SalHouInsSetForNatPhi">6. Salomon&rsquo;s House: Institutional Setting for Natural Philosophy</h2>

<p>
A distinctive feature of Bacon&rsquo;s natural philosophical
<em>oeuvre</em> was his conviction that he could not accomplish his
colossal project on his own. He was continually searching for
patronage but also emphasized the necessity of cooperation and
entertained the idea of a research institute. Bacon considered no form
of the state ideal for the advancement of learning; all of them had
&ldquo;some point of contrariety towards true knowledge&rdquo;.
Whereas &ldquo;monarchies incline wits to profit and pleasure&rdquo;,
republics incline &ldquo;to glory and vanity&rdquo; (SEH III: 252).
This did not, however, thwart him from seeking patronage. He dedicated
<em>The Advancement of Learning</em> to the king and called his
project &ldquo;<em lang="la">Opera Basilica</em>&rdquo; (OFB IV: 61).
The <em>Instauratio magna</em> was, likewise, dedicated to the king,
and Bacon now asked James to instigate &ldquo;the collecting and
perfecting of a true and rigorous natural and experimental
history&rdquo; (OFB XI: 9). No royal patronage was forthcoming,
however. James was well known for his erudition, but his interests in
learning were mainly directed to religious controversies (Kiernan
2000: xxxvii&ndash;lvi). He promised, upon receiving the volume, to
read it and even ask questions about its arguments; but his real view
of the <em>Instauratio magna</em> was &ldquo;that yt is like the peace
of God, that passeth all understanding&rdquo; (<em>Letters of John
Chamberlain</em>, II, 339). Bacon insisted on the need for patronage,
so much so that he even made some effort to seek papal support for
natural histories (Kiernan 2000: lv).</p>

<p>
Another source of help could be universities, and Bacon&rsquo;s
criticism of universities did not prevent him from trying to obtain
their aid. He sent copies of <em>The Advancement of Learning</em> to
the chancellors and other officials of both Cambridge and Oxford, but
eliciting no response, he decided to pursue help from younger scholars
(Kiernan 2000: xxxi&ndash;xxxvii). Bacon also cherished hopes for
international cooperation among European universities because they had
&ldquo;a kind of contract, fraternitie, &amp; correspondence&rdquo;
(OFB IV: 60). International collaboration required, however, peace,
and Bacon, in the early years of the seventeenth century, was sanguine
about the prospects, writing in a famous letter in 1609:</p>

<blockquote>

<p>
Myself am like the miller of Huntingdon, that was wont to pray for
peace amongst the willows; for while the winds blew, the wind-mills
wrought, and the water-mill was less customed. So I see that
controversies of religion must hinder the advancement of sciences.
(SEH XI: 137&ndash;8)</p>
</blockquote>

<p>
Bacon also explored collaboration and its institutional form on a
smaller, but no less significant scale. Already in 1591, he thought
that a political position of power would enable the &ldquo;commandment
of more wits than of a man&rsquo;s own&rdquo; (SEH VIII: 109). In
1594, he argued for the founding of a perfect library, garden and
laboratory (OFB I: 598&ndash;9). He returned to such ideas in his
private notes in 1608, reminding himself of &ldquo;laying for a place
to command wytts and pennes&rdquo;, hiring four scholars to compile
natural histories and inviting &ldquo;many to contribute and
joyne&rdquo;. &ldquo;A college for inventors&rdquo; with a library and
laboratories should be founded. Funding should be available for
traveling and &ldquo;for experiments&rdquo;; cooperation with foreign
universities should be encouraged (SEH XI: 66&ndash;7).</p>

<p>
Nothing came out of these plans. However, they received their most
distinctive expression in Bacon&rsquo;s <em>New Atlantis</em>. It is a
story of a utopian society called Bensalem, whose happiness was
brought about by Salomon&rsquo;s House&mdash;a scientific institution
&ldquo;dedicated to the study of the Works and Creatures of God&rdquo;
(SEH III: 145). Bacon described its laboratories, instruments and
&ldquo;the several employments and functions whereto our fellows are
assigned&rdquo;. Thirty-six fellowships are mentioned by their
different tasks (SEH III: 156).</p>

<p>
Many historians have argued that the nature of Bacon&rsquo;s
cooperative idea was based on his experience as a statesman and that,
therefore, it was elitist and hierarchical (Martin 1991: 105&ndash;40;
Leary 1994: 145&ndash;50; Ash 2004: 205&ndash;7). Bacon sometimes
expressed such views. In 1603, for instance, he planned to publish
some of his ideas &ldquo;to the world&rdquo; but others should be
reserved to &ldquo;some fit and selected minds, and kept
private&rdquo; (SEH X: 287). Nevertheless, he emphasized time and
again that the directions of the <em>Instauratio magna</em> would have
the effect of levelling men&rsquo;s wits. &ldquo;Although the forms of
Polities may be varied&rdquo;, he opined in the preface to the
<em>Instauratio magna</em>, &ldquo;the state of the sciences is
singular, and it has always been and will remain popular&rdquo; (OFB
XI: 15, translation modified). Commenting on the &ldquo;tables of
discovery&rdquo;, he wrote that &ldquo;anyone of moderate insight and
resourcefulness&rdquo; would see remarkable results in them (NO I:
117; OFB XI: 177). He was convinced that, once his precepts were
carefully adopted and implemented, the individual&rsquo;s
characteristics become immaterial. &ldquo;For my way of discovering
sciences&rdquo;, he clarified, &ldquo;nearly equalizes intellects and
leaves little to their brilliance, since it conducts everything
through the most certain rules and demonstrations&rdquo; (NO I: 122;
OFB XI: 185, translation modified).</p>

<p>
What about the structure of Salomon&rsquo;s House? There was a
division of labor between fellows based roughly in different stages of
Bacon&rsquo;s six-part system from &ldquo;Merchants of Light&rdquo;,
who traveled to foreign countries to find out about their recent
inventions, to &ldquo;Interpreters of Nature&rdquo;, whose task was to
formulate &ldquo;greater observations, axioms, and aphorisms&rdquo;
(SEH III: 165). Scholars have argued that this division of labor is
hierarchical, but this is not necessarily the case. It was a duty
roster. Nowhere did Bacon indicate that there was a hierarchy amongst
the tasks different fellows were expected to undertake.
Salomon&rsquo;s House appears to be non-hierarchical. The fellows held
&ldquo;divers meetings and consults of our whole number, to consider
of the former labours and collections&rdquo; (SEH III: 165). This
suggests that all the fellows, whatever their duty, participated in
the decision-making. This emerges even more clearly from the fact that
it was up to the fellows collectively to decide upon the publication
of the results of their inventions. As Bacon&rsquo;s narrator
explained:</p>

<blockquote>

<p>
We have consultations, which of the inventions and experiences which
we have discovered shall be published, and which not: and take all an
oath of secrecy, for concealing of those which we think fit to keep
secret: though some of those we do reveal sometimes to the State, and
some not. (SEH III: 165)</p>
</blockquote>

<p>
The fellows bore the awesome responsibility of their tall order
collectively.</p>

<h2 id="MorPolPhi">7. Moral and Political Philosophy</h2>

<p>
The <em>Instauratio magna</em> pertained to all human knowledge,
including moral and civil philosophy. The position of moral and civil
philosophy in Bacon&rsquo;s colossal project was, however, awkward,
and their relationship with natural philosophy was strained.</p>

<p>
Bacon emphasized, as we have seen, that all sciences shared a stem,
<em>philosophia prima</em>, with common axioms. In the <em>Novum
organum</em>, he asked &ldquo;whether I speak of natural philosophy
alone, or whether I also speak of perfecting the other
sciences&mdash;logic, ethics and politics&rdquo;. He immediately
provided the answer: &ldquo;I do indeed mean it of all the things just
mentioned&rdquo; (NO I: 127; OFB XI: 191). Moreover, natural history
formed the basis of natural philosophy, and Bacon mentioned similar
histories for human philosophy. In the <em>Novum organum</em>, he
promised that there would be a &ldquo;history and tables of discovery
concerning anger, fear, shame and so on, and also ones to do with
examples of civil business&rdquo; as well as about &ldquo;the mental
motions of memory, composition and division, judgment, and the
rest&rdquo; (NO I: 127; OFB XI: 191). Although in &ldquo;A Preparative
to a Natural and Experimental History&rdquo;, he discussed natural
history alone, in the ensuing catalog of particular histories, he had
an extensive list of the histories of humankind. These included
several medical histories and such specific histories as
&ldquo;History of the feelings&rdquo;, &ldquo;History of intellectual
faculties&rdquo; and &ldquo;History of military matters&rdquo; (OFB
XI: 479&ndash;83). These, if completed, would have formed the
foundation of human philosophy just as natural histories were to form
that of natural philosophy (Peltonen 1996a: 293).</p>

<p>
This is clear enough, but several issues complicate it. To begin with,
&ldquo;surely affairs of state differ greatly from the arts&rdquo;,
Bacon wrote. The upshot was that changes in politics, unlike in
natural philosophy, were always highly problematic. In political
matters, &ldquo;even change for the better brings fears of disorder,
since civil government rests not on demonstration but on authority,
consent, reputation and opinion&rdquo; (NO I: 90; OFB XI: 147). More
importantly, in numerous writings, Bacon suggested that moral and
civil philosophy were guided by different methods than natural
philosophy. In around 1607, he criticized the syllogism and praised
induction but noted that the syllogism was well suited to
&ldquo;subjects which are based upon opinion like ethics and
politics&rdquo; (Farrington 1964: 89; SEH III: 607). He repeated the
same message in the <em>Instauratio magna</em>, writing that
&ldquo;the dialectic in current use&rdquo; was &ldquo;very properly
applied to civil questions and the arts which rest on conversation and
opinion&rdquo; (OFB XI: 19). In fact, Bacon went so far as to claim
that &ldquo;the philosophy we are introducing will be quite
useless&rdquo; for &ldquo;civil life&rdquo; [<em lang="la">vitae
ciuilis</em>] (OFB XI: 56).</p>

<p>
There is also a curious discrepancy between Bacon&rsquo;s optimism
over the enormous benefits natural philosophy would bring about and
his view of civil knowledge. Whereas the former would provide &ldquo;a
different universe of things&rdquo;&mdash;things people could not even
comprehend&mdash;the latter held no such promises. Nor did Bacon take
the potential societal benefits of natural philosophy into account in
his civil knowledge. The only glimpse we have of these benefits can be
found in the <em>New Atlantis</em>. Although he described neither the
political arrangements nor the social life of Bensalem in any detail,
there are some interesting clues in the story. The island community
and its inhabitants are repeatedly described as &ldquo;happy;&rdquo;
the people were &ldquo;full of piety and humanity&rdquo;, and the
place appeared to the visitors as &ldquo;this happy and holy
ground&rdquo; (SEH III: 134, 136). When one of the fathers of
Salomon&rsquo;s House came to the city, &ldquo;the street was
wonderfully well kept&rdquo;, and the people stood silently in an
orderly fashion. Even &ldquo;the windows likewise were not crowded,
but every one stood in them as if they had been placed&rdquo; (SEH
III: 155). Underlying this happiness and docility were no doubt the
benefits Salomon&rsquo;s House had provided. Indeed, when the visitors
wondered about the secrecy of the island, they were told that it was
&ldquo;a land of magicians&rdquo;. We should remember that the
operative part of metaphysics in the uppermost echelon of the Baconian
pyramid was magic. The visitors reacted exactly as Bacon had predicted
in the <em>Novum organum</em> that people would respond to the
inventions of &ldquo;Active Science&rdquo;. They could neither grasp
nor even dream of them and agreed that &ldquo;there was something
supernatural in this island&rdquo;. But for them, it was
&ldquo;angelical&rdquo; rather &ldquo;than magical&rdquo; (SEH III:
140).</p>

<p>
When Bacon examined moral and civil knowledge in both <em>The
Advancement of Learning</em> and <em>De augmentis scientiarum</em>,
such spectacular societal results of natural philosophy were nowhere
to be seen. Although &ldquo;happiness&rdquo; was listed in <em>De
augmentis scientiarum</em> as one of the areas of civil knowledge, it
had been &ldquo;excellently handled&rdquo; by earlier philosophers
(SEH V: 79), and Bacon had nothing to add to it. The far-reaching
effects of natural philosophy upon human life had no bearing on moral
and civil knowledge. The themes Bacon explored in these disciplines
were conventional topics in Renaissance moral and political philosophy
although his treatment of them was unconventional. Perhaps the most
obvious departure from the traditional view was his clear separation
of moral philosophy from civil philosophy, and his establishment of
civil knowledge as &ldquo;an entire doctrine by itself&rdquo; (SEH IV:
405). Moral philosophy was concerned with &ldquo;Internall goodnesse:
But ciuile knowledge requireth onelye an Externall goodnesse: for that
as to societye sufficeth&rdquo; (OFB IV: 156).</p>

<p>
Natural philosophy contained both theoretical (physics and
metaphysics) and operative parts (mechanics and magic). In moral
knowledge, there was a comparable separation between the
&ldquo;PLATFORME of GOOD&rdquo; and the &ldquo;CVLTVRE OF THE
MIND&rdquo;. The first described the nature of good, the second was
intended to prescribe rules how to attain it (OFB IV: 135). The nature
of good was again divided into two. Good could be &ldquo;a Totall or
substantiue in it selfe&rdquo;, but it could also be &ldquo;a parte or
Member of a greater Bodye&rdquo;. The latter was to be preferred
because the public was of far greater importance than the individual.
This distinction prompted Bacon to defend the active life vigorously
and to criticize several strands of moral philosophy, including
Aristotelianism, Epicureanism, skepticism and Stoicism for defending
the contemplative life (Peltonen 1995: 141&ndash;5). The culture of
the mind, the second part of moral philosophy, Bacon found woefully
deficient and provided some general remarks towards remedying it.
These included studying different characters and tempers of human
nature, as well as the impact of such factors as gender, age and the
locality.</p>

<p>
As to civil knowledge, Bacon observed in <em>The Advancement of
Learning</em> that &ldquo;in Ciuile matters there is a wisedome of
discourse, and a wisedome of direction&rdquo; (OFB IV: 80). These
seemed to correspond to the theoretical and operative parts of natural
philosophy. However, Bacon did not clarify this remark and, in fact,
withdrew it from <em>De augmentis scientiarum</em>. There was no
theoretical part of civil knowledge, no &ldquo;inquisition of
causes&rdquo; and no clue as to what such a theoretical part of civil
knowledge would have looked like (Peltonen 1996a: 294).</p>

<p>
Civil knowledge had three parts: &ldquo;Conuersation, Negotiation, and
Gouernment&rdquo;. The wisdom of conversation examined courtesy or
civility and their importance in life. Thinking most likely of such
courtesy books as Baldassare Castiglione&rsquo;s <em>The
Courtier</em>, Giovanni Della Casa&rsquo;s <em>Galateo</em> and
Stefano Guazzo&rsquo;s <em>The Ciuile Conuersation</em>, all published
in English in the latter part of the sixteenth century, Bacon observed
that &ldquo;this parte of Ciuile knowledge hath beene elegantlye
handled&rdquo;, and his account of it was very brief. Overall, he
agreed with the earlier authors and underlined the importance of our
outward behavior, reminding his readers that &ldquo;a man maie destroy
the force of his woords with his countenance&rdquo;. (OFB IV:
157&ndash;8).</p>

<p>
&ldquo;The wisedome touching of Negotiation or businesse&rdquo; was
despised by learned men, for which reason it was a completely
neglected discipline. It aimed to teach how to be successful in
private and public life, and it had two parts. The former focused on
advising others, and Bacon used examples from King Solomon&rsquo;s
proverbs, with his brief explanations. The remit of the second part,
&ldquo;Architecture of fortune&rdquo; (OFB IV: 165), was, as the name
implies, how to advance one&rsquo;s career. Bacon defended this wisdom
against accusations of its worthlessness, underlining that it provided
&ldquo;an instrument&rdquo; for &ldquo;higher pursuits&rdquo; (SEH V:
59). His exemplary precepts offered cynical advice on how to carve out
a successful career (&Ccedil;akan forthcoming).</p>

<p>
The final part of civil knowledge was the wisdom of government. In
<em>The Advancement of Learning</em>, Bacon said this wisdom was
&ldquo;secret and retyred&rdquo;. It was both &ldquo;hard to
know&rdquo; but also &ldquo;not fit to vtter&rdquo;, and since he was
writing &ldquo;to a king that is maister of this Science&rdquo;, he
decided &ldquo;to passe ouer this part in silence&rdquo; (OFB IV:
179). By the time he published <em>De augmentis scientiarum</em>, his
view had changed. He still imposed silence on himself but could not
resist the temptation to use this occasion to attempt a political
comeback. &ldquo;Perhaps I might not be&rdquo;, Bacon wrote with
studied moderation, &ldquo;entirely unqualified to handle such topics
with some skill and profit, as being one who has had the benefit of
long experience&rdquo;. He backed this up by a brief assessment of his
political career and issued an equivocal forecast that if he was going
to write anything concerning &ldquo;political knowledge, the work will
perchance be either abortive or posthumous&rdquo; (SEH V: 78&ndash;9).
He now divided the wisdom of government into three parts: the
preservation, the happiness and prosperity and the extension of the
empire. The first two had been excellently treated, but Bacon made a
curious claim that &ldquo;nothing has been said on the last&rdquo;
(SEH V: 79) and provided an exemplary account of the topic.</p>

<p>
Bacon had been preoccupied by the theme of civic greatness for almost
twenty years. He had first mentioned it in an important speech about
naturalization of the Scots in the House of Commons in February 1607
(Peltonen 2012: 151&ndash;5). Around this time, he also wrote an
unfinished manuscript treatise on the true greatness of Britain and
published an essay &ldquo;Of greatnes of Kingdomes&rdquo; in the 1612
edition of <em>The Essaies</em>. The version in <em>De augmentis
scientiarum</em> was subsequently published in English in the final
edition of <em>The Essayes</em> in 1625 with the title &ldquo;Of the
True Greatnesse of Kingdomes and Estates&rdquo;.</p>

<p>
Bacon&rsquo;s claim of novelty in 1623 was curious not so much because
of his earlier ventures into the topic but because in his treatise on
the true greatness of Britain (ca. 1608) he had specifically
emphasized that he was not the first author to explore this topic. He
began that treatise, he explained,</p>

<blockquote>

<p>
by confuting the errors or rather correcting the excesses of certain
immoderate opinions, which ascribe too much to some points of
greatness which are not so essential, and by reducing these points to
a true value and estimation. (SEH VII: 48)</p>
</blockquote>

<p>
The most likely target of Bacon&rsquo;s criticism is relatively easy
to identify, for in 1606 there had appeared an English translation of
Giovanni Botero&rsquo;s <em>Delle cause della grandezza delle
citt&agrave;</em>, originally published in 1588. Botero discussed the
same topic in the introduction to another work, <em>Delle relationi
universali</em>. An edition with this introduction had been published
in English for the first time in 1601 (Botero 1601: 1&ndash;10). It is
worth noting that Bacon and Botero were closely entangled in the 1630
English edition of <em>Delle relationi universali</em>: the
introductory treatise on greatness was considerably enlarged and
silently incorporated parts of Bacon&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;Of the True
Greatnesse of Kingdomes and Estates&rdquo; (Botero 1630:
19&ndash;45).</p>

<p>
It bears emphasis that when Bacon wrote about the greatness of states,
he did not write about &ldquo;their preservation, happiness, and all
other points of well-being&rdquo;, as he had already explained in his
treatise on the true greatness of Britain (SEH VII: 49). These themes
formed their own subdisciplines (of the wisdom of government) and,
therefore, had nothing to do with civic greatness. The true estimation
of civic greatness was the most difficult topic in politics, and
errors in it would have the most &ldquo;perilous consequences&rdquo;.
What did Bacon&rsquo;s account of true greatness involve? He put all
his emphasis on military strength, on &ldquo;the valor and military
disposition of the people&rdquo; (SEH VII: 49). &ldquo;Above
all&rdquo;, he declared, &ldquo;for empire and greatness, it is of
most importance that a nation profess arms as their principal honour,
study, and occupation&rdquo; (SEH V: 84). True greatness was about
military expansion. Bacon repeated this in all of his writings on the
topic and stressed that all other aspects were subject to it. He also
listed &ldquo;the commandment of the sea&rdquo; as an important
element of true greatness (SEH V: 86; VI: 97&ndash;98; VII: 49), which
has prompted many scholars to assume that it was an Atlantic empire
that Bacon chiefly had in mind. However, it has recently been
persuasively argued that more daringly, he was mainly thinking about a
continental European empire, starting from the Netherlands
(Serjeantson 2024).</p>

<h2 id="NatPhiRelLaw">8. Natural Philosophy, Religion and Law</h2>

<p>
Scholars have long debated the relationships in Bacon&rsquo;s
<em>oeuvre</em> between natural philosophy on the one hand and
religion and law, on the other. Bacon was a lawyer by training and
profession and made a dazzling career in law. He also had a life-long
interest in reforming the law. Numerous scholars have suggested that
Bacon&rsquo;s legal and philosophical thought were closely connected
(Shapiro 1983: 168&ndash;9). More specifically, it has been argued
that his legal education and practice played a significant role in his
thinking about natural philosophy. As one scholar has put it:
&ldquo;Bacon&rsquo;s philosophy applied to nature the same model his
jurisprudence applied to the state&rdquo; (Wheeler 1983: 100).</p>

<p>
It is especially Bacon&rsquo;s ideas about natural philosophers
interrogating nature, even torturing it, that have been linked to his
legal thinking and practice. Although this link has been thought to be
fostered by his extensive experience in English common law, it has
recently been shown that it was, in fact, his considerable knowledge
of, and interest in, civil law that helped to shape some key aspects
of his natural philosophy. This is most obvious in his choice of
referring to the investigation of nature as an &ldquo;interpretation
of nature&rdquo;. As Richard Serjeantson has demonstrated, &ldquo;the
idea that nature might be &lsquo;interpreted&rsquo; was alien to the
mental world of the late Renaissance&mdash;alien, that is, until Bacon
proposed it&rdquo;. This choice of terminology was derived from civil
law tradition (Serjeantson 2014).</p>

<p>
Historians have also debated the relationship between religion and
Bacon&rsquo;s natural philosophy. Bacon frequently used religious
imagery in his philosophical writings. He drew a comparison between
religion and natural philosophy and pointed out that, just as in
religion, &ldquo;our faith&rdquo; is shown &ldquo;by works&rdquo;, so
natural philosophy should be judged &ldquo;by its fruits and, if it be
barren, let us regard it as empty&rdquo; (NO I: 73; OFB XI:
117&ndash;19). Not only did he draw close parallels between religion
and natural philosophy, but he also defiantly considered them to
cooperate in the repair of the Fall. Religion and faith could restore
the &ldquo;state of innocence&rdquo;, and &ldquo;the arts and
sciences&rdquo; could restore man&rsquo;s &ldquo;command over created
things&rdquo; (NO II: 52; OFB XI: 447).</p>

<p>
Some scholars have insisted that Bacon&rsquo;s use of religious
language and images in his natural philosophical writings was a mere
camouflage for his secularism and irreligiosity (White 1968;
Weinberger 1985). &ldquo;Bacon&rsquo;s real attitude toward
Christianity was a blend of scepticism, hostility, and
indifference&rdquo;, one interpreter has claimed (Paterson 1987:
422).</p>

<p>
Those who have made the opposite case have argued that we should take
seriously the pervasive religious imagery in Bacon&rsquo;s
philosophical writings centering around salvation and deliverance. The
term &ldquo;instauration&rdquo; entailed, among other things, the
restoration of humanity to its prelapsarian state. Bacon&rsquo;s whole
project of reforming natural philosophy was, these scholars have
insisted,</p>

<blockquote>

<p>
drawn from the Judaeo-Christian scriptures, particularly the Genesis
account of the Creation and the Fall; from [the] apocalyptic
expectation of renewal in the Old Testament; and from soteriological
themes of the New Testament. (McKnight 2006: 3)</p>
</blockquote>

<p>
It has also been suggested that, early on, Bacon moved away from the
Puritan background of his mother and embraced High-Church Anglican
conformism. Lancelot Andrewes (1555&ndash;1626), a conformist scholar
and bishop, and Tobie Matthew (1577&ndash;1655), a Catholic, not only
were Bacon&rsquo;s close friends but had a considerable impact on his
religion and, thus, on his natural philosophy (Matthews 2008).</p>

<p>
Whatever the merits of these opposite positions, two things about the
relationship between Bacon&rsquo;s natural philosophy and religion are
widely accepted. First, he regarded &ldquo;the study of nature as a
truly religious activity&rdquo; (Gascoigne 2010: 215). &ldquo;Natural
philosophy, after the Word of God&rdquo;, Bacon asserted in the
<em>Novum organum</em>, &ldquo;is the best medicine for superstition
and most highly recommended food for faith&rdquo; (NO I: 89; OFB XI:
145). Second, he wanted to keep the study of nature and religion
strictly separated. Each would have a truly harmful effect on the
other (Gascoigne 2010: 216&ndash;18). Natural philosophy, moreover,
required peace to progress, but religious conflicts could easily
escalate into wars. Therefore, &ldquo;controversies of religion must
hinder the advancement of sciences&rdquo; (SEH XI: 137&ndash;8).</p>

<h2 id="BacLeg">9. Bacon&rsquo;s Legacy</h2>

<p>
Bacon&rsquo;s philosophical legacy was large and enduring. Soon after
he published his Latin philosophical works in the early 1620s, they
were widely read and commented on in continental Europe. His first
readers in the Netherlands were Constantijn Huygens (1596&ndash;1687),
who already in 1621 was perusing the <em>Instauratio magna</em>, and
Isaac Beeckman (1588&ndash;1637), who wrote extensive notes on
Bacon&rsquo;s philosophy in the 1620s (Hotson 2020: 73; Rees 2004:
xxiii). The <em>Instauratio magna</em> was taught, for instance, in
Bremen in the late-1620s (Hotson 2020: 165&ndash;6). In France, Pierre
Gassendi (1592&ndash;1655) and Marin Mersenne (1588&ndash;1648) were
particularly keen but critical readers, and Bacon&rsquo;s texts were
also explored by Ren&eacute; Descartes (1596&ndash;1650) and many
others. They acknowledged many of his ideas and even conducted
experiments along the Baconian line but still preferred a more
rationalist approach (P&eacute;rez-Ramos 1996: 312&ndash;14; Buccolini
2014; Jalobeanu 2014). The <em>Instauratio magna</em> traveled quickly
to the Baltic, and the most detailed early criticism of it was written
in the Baltic town of Elbing around 1626&ndash;7 by David Mylius, a
teacher in the local Gymnasium, who defended old-style syllogistic
logic against Bacon. Caspar Streso (1603&ndash;1664), a young German
theologian and a convinced Baconian, quickly rushed to Bacon&rsquo;s
defense (Serjeantson forthcoming).</p>

<p>
In England, one of the earliest and most important Baconians was
Samuel Hartlib (c. 1600&ndash;62), a native of Elbing. He was likely
responsible for Mylius&rsquo;s acquaintance with the <em>Instauratio
magna</em> and certainly behind Streso&rsquo;s familiarity with
Mylius&rsquo;s critique of it (Serjeantson forthcoming). Hartlib,
together with Jan Amos Comenius (1592&ndash;1670) and John Dury
(1596&ndash;1680), promoted Baconian ideas about science and
technology and their utility and benefit during the revolutionary
decades of the 1640s and 1650s (Rees 2004: xxiv; Hotson 2020:
265&ndash;301; Webster 1975). The foundation of the Royal Society in
1660 marked the peak of Bacon&rsquo;s reputation and the
&ldquo;victory of the Baconian project of collaboration, utility, and
progress in natural inquiries&rdquo; (P&eacute;rez-Ramos 1996: 316).
Bacon&rsquo;s theory of induction, along with his natural histories
and experimentalism, significantly inspired the emergence of
experimental philosophy and empiricism in the late seventeenth century
(Anstey &amp; Vanzo 2023). He was also invoked to justify Newton, but
quickly, Newtonian science was employed to vindicate Baconianism (Rees
2004: xxvi). During the Enlightenment, Bacon&rsquo;s fame was equally
great: Voltaire and Rousseau, Condorcet and d&rsquo;Alembert praised
him and his philosophical achievements. They largely overlooked
Bacon&rsquo;s methodological insights and, like those in revolutionary
England in the mid-seventeenth century, regarded the Baconian project
as about science and technology harnessed to societal needs
(P&eacute;rez-Ramos 1996: 320&ndash;1).</p>

<p>
Many British philosophers paid homage to Bacon in the early nineteenth
century while critically examining his methodological injunctions.
Soon, however, his reputation as a philosopher started to wane, and he
was no longer seen as having provided the methodology for subsequent
natural philosophy and science (P&eacute;rez-Ramos 1996: 321&ndash;7;
Rees 2004: xxvii&ndash;xxxi). Such criticism continued in the
twentieth century when many epistemologists emphasized that Bacon was
&ldquo;a champion of what science has never been and will never
be&rdquo; (Rossi 1996, 43). The Frankfurt School took up the
Enlightenment view of Bacon but turned it upside down, castigating him
as responsible for the modern scientific domination of nature and
humankind. More recent scholarship has underlined Bacon&rsquo;s
seminal importance in early modern philosophy. His <em>Instauratio
magna</em>, with its emphasis on operative science, collaboration and
a new method, has been given a central place in historical accounts of
the birth of the new science (Rees 2004: xl&ndash;xlvi).</p>
</div>

